The paper deals with lower bounds for linear locally correctable codes (LCCs), which are codes that allow for efficient correction of errors in a small number of locations. This falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also uses techniques from convex geometry, dimension reduction, and graph theory, which are relevant to the sub-categories of computational geometry (cs.CG), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and computational complexity (cs.CC) respectively. Additionally, the paper involves combinatorial arguments and probabilistic analysis, which are relevant to the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
